## Migration: `TimedExecutor` â†’ .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Remove entirely |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** â€” the runtime no longer supports forcibly injecting exceptions into threads. You must switch to cooperative cancellation.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable â€” always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if Task.Run's body doesn't check the token.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ag) when (ag.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ag.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Changes

1. **`Thread` + `Abort()` â†’ `Task.Run` + `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)`** â€” the CTS auto-cancels after the timeout.
2. **`ThreadAbortException` â†’ `OperationCanceledException`** â€” the `when` guard distinguishes timeout from external cancellation.
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` â†’ removed** â€” no equivalent needed; cooperative cancellation doesn't inject exceptions.
4. **`using var cts`** â€” prevents timer/callback leaks.

### âš ď¸Ź Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is *cooperative*. `Task.WaitAsync` unblocks the caller, but the delegate keeps running on the thread pool. If `work` is CPU-bound and never checks a token, it runs to completion in the background. |
| **To truly stop work** | Accept a `CancellationToken` in the delegate and check it: |

```csharp
// Better: pass the token into the work so it can cooperate
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
        return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller cooperates by checking the token:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If `work` calls a library you can't modify, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` â€” that's the only way to forcibly stop uncooperative code in modern .NET. |
| **Blocking I/O ignores tokens** | Synchronous calls like `socket.Receive()` won't respond to cancellation. Use async overloads (`ReceiveAsync(ct)`) instead. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at this top-level orchestration point. Let it propagate everywhere else. |
